@prithvirajsen For that example, `W` would be a single row that looks like `1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8`.  The shape would be `(C, F*Hf*Wf) = (1, 2*2*2)`.  Essentially, we are just taking the normal `(F, C, Hf, Wf)` filter tensor, transposing it to `(C, F, Hf, Wf)` and then flattening the latter three dimensions as usual to `(C, F*Hf*Wf)`.

The motivation here is to think about the shape of `W` during a regular 2D conv function, i.e. `(F, C, Hf, Wf)`.  In the forward *and* backward pass of regular 2D conv, `W` maintains the same `(F, C, Hf, Wf)`shape.  Specifically, in the backward pass, the data gradient function `conv2d_backward_data` accepts the same `W` of shape `(F, C, Hf, Wf)` to map from gradients wrt the output of shape `(N, F, Hout, Wout)` to gradients wrt to the input of shape `(N, C, Hin, Win)`.

In a 2D transpose conv function, we use the 2D conv data gradient function as the forward function.  If we use the same size terminology as from regular 2D conv, we would be mapping from an input with `F` channels to an output with `C` channels (which seems backward, but is correct since the forward pass of 2D transpose conv is defined as the backward pass of 2D conv), and we would be using the same filter `W` of shape `(F, C, Hf, Wf)`.  Now, in order to make the terminology of the 2D transpose conv layer consistent with the rest of the library, we would need to swap the variable names `F` and `C` so that we are mapping from an input with `C` channels to an output with `F` channels.  Thus, we would use a filter `W` of shape `(C, F, Hf, Wf`).

